We start by expressing the complex number z in terms of its real and imaginary parts. Let $z = x + yi$, where $x$ and $y$ are real numbers. Then, we have
\begin{align*}
|z - 1| &= |(x - 1) + yi| = \sqrt{(x - 1)^2 + y^2}, \\
|z + 3| &= |(x + 3) + yi| = \sqrt{(x + 3)^2 + y^2}, \\
|z - i| &= |x + (y - 1)i| = \sqrt{x^2 + (y - 1)^2}.
\end{align*}
Since these three expressions are equal, we have
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{(x - 1)^2 + y^2} &= \sqrt{(x + 3)^2 + y^2}, \\
\sqrt{(x - 1)^2 + y^2} &= \sqrt{x^2 + (y - 1)^2}.
\end{align*}
Squaring both sides of these equations, we get
\begin{align*}
(x - 1)^2 + y^2 &= (x + 3)^2 + y^2, \\
(x - 1)^2 + y^2 &= x^2 + (y - 1)^2.
\end{align*}
Simplifying, we get
\begin{align*}
x - 1 &= x + 3, \\
x - 1 &= y - 1.
\end{align*}
Therefore, $x = -2$ and $y = 1$. Thus, $z = -2 + i.$</think> <answer> $z = -2 + i$ </answer>
